There are many ways to facilitate templated queries. Here we use Python via reticulate and Jinja2. As another example, see this R approach.

library(reticulate)
## Warning: package 'reticulate' was built under R version 3.4.1
jinja = import("jinja2")
# If you get an error, in the shell run:
#    pip install jinja2
py = import_builtins()

perform_bqquery = function(sql_path, ...) {
  sql = jinja$Template(py$open(sql_path, "r")$read())$render(params)
  cat(sql)
  query_exec(sql, use_legacy_sql = FALSE, project=params$PROJECT_ID, ...)
}

Compute cell metrics

cell_metrics = perform_bqquery(
  sql_path = "cell_metrics.sql",
  destination_table = params$CELL_METRICS_TABLE,
  write_disposition = params$WRITE_DISPOSITION,
  max_pages = Inf)
#standardSQL
  --
  -- Compute the number of all transcripts and mitochondrial transcripts per cell.
  --
SELECT
  cell,
  SUM(trans_cnt) AS alltrans,
  SUM(IF(gene IN (SELECT gene FROM `orr_bp.gene_table`),
      trans_cnt,
      0)) AS mttrans,
  COUNT(DISTINCT gene) AS gene_cnt
FROM
  `scalable-analysis-playground.mouse_retinal_bipolar.scrna_seq`
WHERE
  trans_cnt > 0
GROUP BY
  cell

Visualize cell metrics

plot_metrics = function(data, x, xlab, title) {
  gg = ggplot(data, aes_string(x)) +
    geom_histogram(col="red", aes(fill=..count..)) +
    scale_x_log10(labels=comma) +
    scale_y_log10(labels=comma) +
    scale_fill_continuous(labels=comma) +
    xlab(paste(xlab, "(log scale)")) +
    ylab(paste("Frequency (log scale)")) +
    ggtitle(paste("Histogram:", title))
  return(gg)
}
plot(sort(cell_metrics$gene_cnt),

Choose quality control thresholds and compute the cell subset

perform_bqquery(sql_path = "passing_cells.sql",
                destination_table = params$PASSING_CELLS_TABLE,
                write_disposition = params$WRITE_DISPOSITION,
                page_size = 10,
                max_pages = 1)
#standardSQL
  --
  -- Identify cells that pass the quality control criteria.  These thresholds are based on
  -- those in https://github.com/broadinstitute/BipolarCell2016.  Update them as needed for
  -- the data to which they are being applied.
  --
SELECT
  cell
FROM
  `orr_bp.cell_metrics`
WHERE
  0.1 > mttrans/alltrans
  AND gene_cnt BETWEEN 501 AND 23000

Compute gene metrics

gene_metrics = perform_bqquery(
  sql_path = "gene_metrics.sql",
  destination_table = params$GENE_METRICS_TABLE,
  write_disposition = params$WRITE_DISPOSITION,
  max_pages = Inf)
#standardSQL
  --
  -- Compute the number of all transcripts and passing cells per gene.
  --
SELECT
  gene,
  SUM(trans_cnt) AS alltrans,
  COUNT(DISTINCT cell) AS cell_cnt
FROM
  `scalable-analysis-playground.mouse_retinal_bipolar.scrna_seq`
WHERE
  trans_cnt > 0
  AND cell IN (
  SELECT
    cell
  FROM
    `orr_bp.passing_cells`)
GROUP BY
  gene

Choose quality control thresholds and compute the gene subset

perform_bqquery(sql_path = "passing_genes.sql",
                destination_table = params$PASSING_GENES_TABLE,
                write_disposition = params$WRITE_DISPOSITION,
                page_size = 10,
                max_pages = 1)
#standardSQL
  --
  -- Identify genes that pass the quality control criteria.  These thresholds are based on
  -- those in https://github.com/broadinstitute/BipolarCell2016.  Update them as needed for
  -- the data to which they are being applied.
  --
SELECT
  gene
FROM
  `orr_bp.gene_metrics`
WHERE
  30 < cell_cnt
  AND 60 < alltrans

perform_bqquery(sql_path = "passing_data_counts.sql")
#standardSQL
  --
  -- Count the number of distinct cells and genes in this dataset.
  --

  COUNT(DISTINCT gene) AS passing_gene_cnt,
  COUNT(DISTINCT cell) AS passing_cell_cnt
FROM
  `scalable-analysis-playground.mouse_retinal_bipolar.scrna_seq`
WHERE
  cell IN (
    SELECT
      cell
    FROM
      `orr_bp.passing_cells`)
  AND
  gene IN (
    SELECT
      gene
    FROM
      `orr_bp.passing_genes`)
